  "prompt": "Does my duck have hypothermia?",
  "response": "I'm not equipped to diagnose health conditions, including hypothermia, in animals. However, I can provide you with some general information. Ducks are generally hardy animals, but they can suffer from hypothermia if exposed to extreme cold, particularly if they are wet or if they do not have proper shelter.\n\nSigns of hypothermia in ducks may include:\n\n- Shivering or shaking\n- Lethargy or weakness\n- Unresponsiveness or decreased activity\n- Stiffness or difficulty moving\n- Pale or bluish extremities (like the bill or feet)\n\nIf you suspect your duck might have hypothermia, it's important to take action to warm them up gradually and get them to a vet for professional care. You can move the duck to a warm, dry area, provide blankets or towels, and offer warm (not hot) water to drink. Avoid heating the duck too rapidly.\n\nPlease consult a veterinarian for accurate diagnosis and treatment.",
